{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772638426,"nonce":"6WCb/so29DgKh7lkSqcE096CxjU=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87vxF_C","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/345","origin":"github"},"title":"Evaluate local-first development workflow with git-bug and lightweight forge","message":"## Summary\n\nEvaluate a **local-first development workflow** where daily work happens locally with git-bug for issue tracking and a lightweight local forge (Forgejo/Gitea) for repo hosting, and GitHub becomes a publication/collaboration channel synced when convenient.\n\nThis shifts the framing from \"survive GitHub outages\" to \"work locally-first, sync to GitHub when ready.\"\n\n## Motivation\n\n- GitHub has had multiple major outages in 2025–2026 (Azure migration instability), blocking pushes, CI, PRs, and reviews\n- Field deployments already use a local GitLab instance on the robot network for repo sync — but GitLab is heavyweight (~4-8GB RAM) for that role\n- The workspace's issue-first workflow, worktree scripts, and PR review process all depend on `gh` CLI / GitHub availability\n- Core development (git, colcon build/test, pre-commit) is already fully local — the gaps are in governance and collaboration tooling\n\n## Proposed Architecture\n\n```\nDaily work (local / robot network):\n  git-bug         → primary issue tracker (distributed, offline-first)\n  Forgejo/Gitea   → lightweight local forge (repo hosting, web UI, ~200MB RAM)\n  act / colcon    → local CI (run GitHub Actions workflows via Docker)\n  pre-commit      → local linting and checks\n\nSync to GitHub (when ready for external review):\n  git push github              → sync code\n  git bug bridge push github   → sync issues\n  gh pr create                 → open PR for Copilot review + CI\n```\n\n## Key Components to Evaluate\n\n### 1. git-bug as primary issue tracker\n- Distributed, offline-first bug tracker stored in `refs/bugs/` (no working tree clutter)\n- Bidirectional bridges to GitHub, GitLab, and Gitea/Forgejo\n- Conflict-free merging via Lamport timestamps\n- CLI, TUI, and web UI interfaces\n- Issues travel with the repo via normal `git push/pull`\n- Bridge-per-repo setup needed for each project repo\n- [git-bug repo](https://github.com/git-bug/git-bug)\n\n### 2. Forgejo/Gitea as lightweight local forge\n- Replace heavyweight GitLab instance on robot network\n- ~200MB RAM, runs on Raspberry Pi or any small box\n- Built-in issue tracker, web UI for code browsing\n- Docker one-liner deployment\n- Forgejo Actions (GitHub Actions–compatible with minor tweaks)\n- [Forgejo](https://forgejo.org/) / [Gitea](https://gitea.com/)\n\n### 3. Workspace script adaptation\n- Worktree scripts currently require `gh` for issue title verification\n- Refactor to use git-bug for issue lookup as primary, `gh` only when syncing\n- Define clear online/offline detection\n- This is a workflow shift, not just graceful degradation\n\n### 4. Local CI with act\n- Run `.github/workflows/` locally via Docker\n- Pre-cache `ros:jazzy-ros-core` image for offline use\n- Complements pre-commit hooks: hooks catch style, act catches build/test\n- Could be primary CI (not just fallback)\n- [nektos/act](https://github.com/nektos/act)\n\n### 5. Sync protocol\n- Define when and how to push to GitHub\n- Could be a `make sync-github` target: push repos + `git bug bridge push`\n- Document the workflow for both humans and agents\n\n### 6. Local LLM for PR review (longer-term)\n- Ollama + coding model (Qwen 2.5 Coder, DeepSeek Coder, etc.)\n- Feed diff + governance context (principles, ADRs) for review\n- Lower quality than Copilot/Claude but catches mechanical issues offline\n- Depends on available hardware on the robot network\n\n## Research References\n\nSee [research digest entry](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/pull/344) for detailed source links covering:\n- GitHub outage patterns and resilience strategies (2025–2026)\n- git-bug architecture and GitHub bridge\n- act for local CI\n- Self-hosted git platform comparison (Forgejo vs Gitea vs GitLab)\n- ROS 2 offline development patterns\n\n## Suggested Approach\n\n1. **Evaluate git-bug** — install, test GitHub bridge against one project repo\n2. **Evaluate Forgejo** — Docker deployment, test as GitLab replacement\n3. **Prototype the local-first workflow** — manual walkthrough of the daily + sync cycle\n4. **Adapt scripts** — refactor worktree scripts for local-first\n5. **Add local CI** — integrate act\n6. **Document** — sync protocol, agent instructions for local-first workflow\n\nSub-issues will be created for each component as evaluation progresses.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}